defaultits principles of patient care without pre
defaultjudice. [4]
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultShaare Zedek defaultMedical CentredefaultShaare Zedek UK raises vital funds to support the work of the Shaare Zedek Medical Centre in Jerusalem. 
defaultLiterally meaning 
default“Gates of Righteousness,” Shaare Zedek has responded to the needs of Jerusalem’s uniquely diverse population from its very first day of operation 
defaultin 1902
default;
default treating patients of every race, religio
defaultn and nationality
default regardless of financial circumstances. 
defaultMedi
defaultcal excellence, patient dignity and a compassionate individualised approach to all
default are core to our
default mission
default. 
defaultAdditionally, t
defaulthe 
default1,000 bed 
defaulthospital maintains its reputation as an internationally-regarded research and teaching hospital, committed to advancing 
defaultscientific progress, innovation and technology.
default [5]
defaultShaare Zedek, with its century-long tradition of offering quality medical care to all in Jerusalem, has been a highly positive force in the city’
defaults development
default and has contributed greatly to residents’ qua
defaultlity of life.
default&#xa0;
default Today, it is considered to be in the top echelon of med
defaultical institutions in Israel, despite receiving 
defaultno government funding
default 
defaultfor equipment, development or research. 
default[6]
defaultCoexistence as a way of lifedefaultVisiting dignitaries
default,
default including British Parliamentarians
default,
default often ask about 
defaultefforts taken to advance
default coexistence at the hospital. Coexistence is a way of life 
defaultat Shaare Zedek. 
defaultPatient ethnicity is not recorded upon admission but the hospital 
defaultestimates that 
defaultthe ethnic makeup of 
defaultits patient population is very similar to th
defaultat
default of Jerusalem as a whole; 
defaultapproximately 70
default% Jewish, 30% Arab. Our patients are referred from all over Israel and surrounding areas including 
defaultt
defaulthe 
defaultPalesti
defaultnian Territories
default and other countries including the United 
defaultArab 
defaultEmirates
default.
default [7]
defaultOur staff also 
defaultclosely mirrors
default Jerusalem’s ethnic and religious composition.
default&#xa0;
default We have several senior staff members from the Arab and Palestinian communities, including our chief cardiothoracic surgeon, a senior anesthetist, a senior uro
defaultlogist, and a senior cardiologist.
default [8]
defaultCertain departments of the hospital have a patient mix which varies significantly from the average for a variety of reasons.
default&#xa0;
default For instance, approximately two-thirds of the patients in our 
defaultPaediatric
default Dialysis Unit are Arabs, because of a genetic predisposition in that population to kidney disease.
default 
defaultI
defaultn order to better meet the edu
defaultcational and social needs of the
defaultse
default yo
defaultung patients and their families, the 
defaultPaediatric
default Dialysis Unit
default has an Arab social worker 
defaultand an Arab teacher on staff. 
default [9]
defaultInterestingly, while in the “outside world,” there is minimal contact between ultra-Orthodox Jews and Arabs, in the 
defaultP
defaulta
defaultediatric
default Dialysis Unit, 
defaultpatients and families 
defaultfrom both cultures 
defaultmix freely.
default&#xa0;
default Families with children su
defaultffering from kidney disease find that they have much more in common than that which divides them.
default This sense of community was witnessed by 
defaultCouncillor
default Vikki Slade on a recent visit to the hospital:
default [9]
default“These children have to come into the hospital on a 
defaultdaily or alternate daily basis, something which has an incredible impact on the family lives of those involved. I was heartened to watch parents sit with children from the opposite side of the political divide while their own parents went to pick up other 
defaultsiblings from school or leave the bedside for other reasons.”
default [10]
defaultShaare Zedek’s approach is not to ignore religious and ethnic differences; it is rather to show respect for them.
default&#xa0;
default This approach is demonstrated in a number of areas.
default&#xa0;
default A perfect example t
defaultakes place in the M
defaultuslim
default month of Ramadan, when religiously observant Muslims fast from sunrise to sunset.
default&#xa0;
default Shaare
default Zedek provides a special 
defaultmeal for its Muslim staff members, scheduled to begin precisely at sunset.
default 
default[11]
default&#xa0;
defaultArabdefault patientsdefaultThe policy 
defaultof 
default“political blindness” comes at a great cost to the hospital.
default&#xa0;
default While Israeli citizens are entitled by law to health coverage through one of the country’s health funds, non-citizens like those who com
defaulte from the Palestinian Authority
default have no such coverage and
default often these cases are completely uninsured.
default [12]
defaultWhile severe limitations have been placed on the number of patients coming into Israel from the P
defaultalestinian 
defaultA
defaultuthority
default, there are still a significant number of Palestinians being treated in Israeli hospitals
default, including Shaare Zedek.
default&#xa0;
default The cost to the hospital to treat these largely uninsured patients is well in excess of $100,000 per year.
default [13]
defaultDespite this
default, it is our pledge as a modern medical 
defaultcent
defaultre
default driven 
defaultby compassion and not politics 
defaultto ensure that when a
default patient arrives at our doors in need of help, he or she will not be deprived.
default 
default[14]
defaultA story which illustrates th
defaultis approach is t
defaulthat of a three year 
defaultold girl rushed to Shaare Zedek from Nablus with severe kidney failure. The close relationship between the h
defaultead of the hospital in Nablus and the head of 
defaultPaediatric
default Nephrology at Shaare Zedek meant one phone call ensured a crash team were waiting for her on arrival. She died on the operating table but the medical team managed to stabilize her and brought her bac
defaultk to life after which she made 
defaulta remarkable
default recovery in the care of the 
defaultPaediatric
default Dialysis Unit. 
defaultThis life saving collaboration was only possible 
defaultbecause of the 
defaultclose relationship between the 
defaulttwo 
defaultdoctors. Shaare Zedek 
defaultwas
default 
defaultfully 
defaultaware that there was no aut
defaulthorization from the Palestinian Authority to treat her
default and even if such authorization had been given it would not have covered most of the cost of the treatment. 
defaultShaare Ze
defaultdek covered the full cost of the girl’s
default treatment. 
defaultSuch stories are a regular occurre
defaultnce at Shaare Zedek
default and are part of the hospital’s contribution to peace
defaultful coexistence
default.  
