defaultCoexistence at times of political conflictdefaultShaare Zedek is not immune to the effects of terrorism. The direct impact on the number of patients and the 
defaultincreased demand for emergency and trauma medicine is immense. During such periods staff-
defaultoften 
defaultincluding those whose family members have been victims of attacks- continue their work on the 
defaultunderstanding that those who enter our doors 
defaultare patients first and
default foremost
default and the duty of doctors and nurses is to heal.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultFollowing a shooting during the Second Intifada one young patient recounted how a team of Arab and Jewish doctors had brought her back to life:
default [16]
default“
defaultA bullet ripped through my chest and into my lun
defaultg. Two women were killed during that attack and dozens more, beside me, were wounded.
default 
defaultI was taken by ambulance to Shaare Zedek Medical Centre and by the time we made it to the hospital, I had no pulse and no blood pressure. I was considered dead on arrival
default. Through the skilled hands of Dr. Shuli Silberman and Dr. Mahar Deeb, a Jewish and Arab doctor working together, they performed a miracle and brought me back to life. After the surgery, was a long recovery process. My after-care specialist, Dr. Salah Odat
defaultallah, stayed by my side through my stay in the ICU and then in the regular ward. But that was not enough. During my stay we formed a strong bond and when I was given permission to return to Chicago, he insisted he fly back with me to ensure my safe return
default.
default”
default [17]
defaultShaare Zedek also treated a number of Arab victims of terror attacks during the Intifada.
default One victim, 
defaultIbrahim
default,
default explained the importance of a social workers’ support for his brother after they were both brought to Shaare Zedek 
defaultsuffering injuries fr
defaultom a bus bombing
default:
default [18]
default “For him to see just how much the staff cares about him, the way everyone wants to help, has made a big difference to him.”
default [19]
default&#xa0;
defaultResearch default&#xa0;defaultIn the area of research, we have conducted a number of studies in cooperation with 
defaultJordanian and Palestinian physicians and hospitals, including a comparative study of the use of pain medication for cancer patients in various institutions, and a genetics study to identify mutations associated with a high risk of breast cancer.
default&#xa0;
default Cooperati
defaultve research with Palestinian institutions has been curtailed to some extent because the risk of terrorism has impeded travel, but staff members on both sides are doing their best to continue working together.
default [20]
defaultBeing 
defaultbased in the heart of Jerusalem
default,
default Sha
defaultare Zedek is fortunate to have a diverse population of people with a wide ethnic pool
default which provides
default a 
defaultfantastic 
defaultresou
defaultrce for research. Recent studies 
defaultlooking specifically at Jewish and Arab populations 
defaultinclude research into 
defaultchildren
default’
defaults smoking habits 
default and
default diabetes
default.
default [21]
default&#xa0;
defaultA major focus of research int
defaulto inherited diseases
default is identifying the mutations responsible for genetic diseases in children. In Jerusalem, marriage between relatives or within a small ethnic group is still common and
default,
default combined with large 
defaultfamily size, this results in a higher frequency of genetic diseases in children. Some diseases are common, e.g. Tay Sachs, which is now prevented by prior testing, but many of these often devastating diseases are specific to a particular family. Advances i
defaultn genetic technology make it possible to identify the mutation causing the disease. This can help the family prevent further affected children (e.g. by 
defaultpre-implantation genetic diagnosis
default) and also provides important insights into the functions of various g
defaulten
defaultes. We have already identified seven new disease genes in the past three
default years.
default [22]
default&#xa0;
defaultResearch activity in the Medical Genetics Institute includes collaboration with Palestinian colleagues to determine inherited mutations that affect breast cancer risk 
defaultin Arab women
default. The Breast Health Centre is 
defaultalso 
defaultworking on a comparative study examining the characteristics 
defaultand stages of diagnosis 
defaultof Arab 
defaultand Jewish 
defaultbreast cancer patients 
defaultin Jerusalem
default.
default [23]
default&#xa0;defaultShaare Zedek &amp; UK defaultGovernment defaultShaare Zedek’s collaborative 
defaultapproach to medicine was first raised in Parliament by Lord Turnberg during a Parliamentary debate in 2003:
default [24]
default default“I was very encouraged by a meeting that I had with representatives of the Shaare Zedek Hospital in Jerusalem, who described efforts that they
default were making to work with a major hospital in Amman in Jordan and in Ramallah in the Palestinian territories. They were developing plans jointly to provide humanitarian aid of a medical type in a co-ordinated way for the survivors of conflicts in Iraq and 
defaultother places in the Middle East. Will it be possible for the UK to work with those organisations to support them and others which are working in a co-ordinated operation?”
default [25]
defaultThis project did not receive support from UK Government but contact remains be
defaulttween the institutions. 
default[26]
defaultWe would welcome a visit by the 
defaultCommittee to the hospital to gain a greater understanding of Shaare Zedek’s work in medical collaboration across communities. 
